<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><img src="http://www.edenhrconsulting.com/images/stories/eden-stick-figures/eden-people-policies.jpg" alt="eden-people-policies" style="float: right; padding-bottom: 15px; padding-left: 15px;" height="225" width="300" />Since the last labour government came to power in 1996, the emphasis on policies relating to the family have steadily increased. Maternity leave has been lengthened, and paternity leave and the right to request flexible working have come in to force. I’m sure that those with children will appreciate the thought and reasoning behind such legislation, however, it can create a substantial additional paperwork burden for the employer.</p>
<p>That said, family friendly policies, if well structured and implemented can aid the engagement of employees and assist in creating a committed, qualified and competent workforce.</p>
<p><strong>Family friendly practices include:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Maternity leave and pay</li>
<li>Parental leave</li>
<li>Paternity leave and pay</li>
<li>Scheme of time off for emergencies</li>
<li>Job sharing</li>
<li>Term-time working</li>
<li>Working at or from home during normal working hours</li>
<li>Ability to change form full to part-time hours</li>
<li>Workplace or other nursery provision</li>
<li>Help with child-care costs</li>
<li>Flexi-time</li>
<li>Time off for IVF treatment</li>
<li>Adoption leave and pay</li>
</ul>
<p>All of the above have requirements on notification to staff, paperwork and practical implementation aspects. Let Eden HR Consulting structure your policies and help you to implement them in a way to engage your employees. In addition, doing it correctly and fairly can greatly reduce the risk of dispute or tribunal claims whilst optimising your staff engagement.</p></td>
</tr>

</table>
